He was accepted on an international drugs trial of Avastin and has now been given the all clear, after the tumours disappeared. Avastin is more commonly used to treat bowel cancer and breast cancer that has spread to other sites in the body.

When his parents Sophie and Simon Lee, 37, first took Oliver to hospital with stomach pain in November 2011, doctors thought he had constipation.

But Ms Maloney from Nottingham told doctors at the Queen's Medical Centre she was sure it was something more serious.

Doctors then found the tumours which were diagnosed as rhabdomyosarcoma, a type of soft tissue sarcoma - a cancer that starts in muscles.

There are only around 60 cases of this type of tumour in the UK each year.

